Moral dilemmas for Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had inflated further in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government has taken on Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac's debt in full, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that the inadequate financial means of their creditors cannot cover.
Why such a rescue action in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Don't those venerable principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Isn't it fair that now innocent taxpayers must bear the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Above all, it remains unclear whether the bailout will ultimately cost US taxpayers anything. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, it cannot be inferred that they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a bailout by the US government could have undermined trust in government securities and, by association, other financial instruments as well.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven by remarkable speculative highs and crashes of asset values over the past few years, introducing questions of trust, but also of fairness into the equation.
In many other countries, similar speculative highs in the housing sector are coming to an end, and they may be facing the same pains – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
The problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007, and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Indian Sensex rose by a factor of 5 between 2003 and 2007 in real terms and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar stock market highs and crashes have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they persisted, the preceding boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a decline in trust could hit the global economy and push it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to prop up the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when help is absent in the face of collapsing markets.
The people's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described boom-and-bust cycles have caused a large redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or in real estate did well or poorly depending on their timing.
The people will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what they were told and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What were people in all these countries told about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really add up to the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
The government can only react in general terms and cannot handle each case individually.
The economic growth of recent times was spectacular in many countries.
Were the capital investments in their markets sold too dearly?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere lured people into believing that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, despite a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice subject to caveat – most of the losers in this game will not be left to starve.
However, we cannot remain indifferent and conclude that all their losses should be left unmitigated.
The nagging problem is one of "good faith".
Economies thrive only when "good faith" prevails.
The current situation, in which speculative highs drove the global economy – and now, after their collapse, are pushing it into recession – suggests that people who touted certain investments acted in bad faith.
Take the investors who bought Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even acknowledged that there was a housing bubble.
The government's top officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering the power of capitalism and its ability to transform and reshape economies.
However, the translation of the given sentence is actually provided in the English summary, which is: "The key issue is maintaining 'good faith' in economies, which is essential for their growth and success."
An unfair treatment can be fatal to economic growth, as it means people lose trust in companies and are therefore less willing to invest their precious capital and labor in them.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
